                                      "value": "The memory model for an ndarray admits arbitrary strides in         each dimension to advance to the next element of the array.         Often, however, you need to interface with code that expects a         C-contiguous or a Fortran-contiguous memory layout. In         addition, an ndarray can be misaligned (the address of an         element is not at an integral multiple of the size of the         element) which can cause your program to crash (or at least         work more slowly) if you try and dereference a pointer into         the array data. Both of these problems can be solved by         converting the Python object into an array that is more         \"well-behaved\" for your specific usage."
